The flux \( F \) at a distance \( d \) from a star is given by the formula: \[ F = \frac{L}{4\pi d^2} \] Rearranging this formula to solve for luminosity \( L \): \[ L = 4\pi d^2 F \] First, we convert the distance from kiloparsecs (kpc) to centimeters (cm). The distance to the star is 800 kpc, which is: \[ 800 \text{ kpc} = 800 \times 10^3 \text{ pc} = 8 \times 10^5 \text{ pc} \] \[ 1 \text{ pc} = 3.08567758 \times 10^{18} \text{ cm} \] \[ 8 \times 10^5 \text{ pc} = 8 \times 3.08567758 \times 10^5 \times 10^{18} \text{ cm} \] \[ = 2.468542064 \times 10^{24} \text{ cm} \] Next, we calculate the square of the distance: \[ d^2 = (2.468542064 \times 10^{24} \text{ cm})^2 \] \[ = 6.0937576 \times 10^{48} \text{ cm}^2 \] We then multiply this by \( 4\pi \): \[ 4\pi \times 6.0937576 \times 10^{48} \text{ cm}^2 \] \[ \approx 12.566370614 \times 6.0937576 \times 10^{48} \text{ cm}^2 \] \[ \approx 76.56922 \times 10^{48} \text{ cm}^2 \] Finally, we multiply by the flux \( F = 10^{-12} \text{ erg} \cdot \text{s}^{-1} \cdot \text{cm}^{-2} \): \[ L = 76.56922 \times 10^{48} \text{ cm}^2 \times 10^{-12} \text{ erg} \cdot \text{s}^{-1} \cdot \text{cm}^{-2} \] \[ = 7.656922 \times 10^{37} \text{ erg} \cdot \text{s}^{-1} \] Rounding to two significant figures, the luminosity of the star is: \[ \boxed{7.66 \times 10^{37}} \text{ erg/s} \]
